> Just like Britain, Peru loves its beans, which they call 'frijoles'! That's where frejolada, this wholesome and warming bean stew, gets its name from. It's finished with a sprinkling of fresh coriander, onion pickle and cooling soured cream for a flavour adventure.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{90%g} and fry until it starts to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed), then coarsely grate (no need to peel).

Add half the onion to a #small bowl{}, cover with the @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and @sugar{1%tsp} for the pickle. Season with a pinch of @salt{} and set aside to pickle.

Once cooked, transfer the chorizo to a #plate{} lined with #baking paper{}. Keep the pan with the chorizo oil.

Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice is cooking, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Return the (now empty) frying pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @?oil{} if needed.

Once hot, add the carrot, remaining onion and half the remaining coriander. Cook until the veg is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir through the garlic, black beans, cooked chorizo and @Central American style spice mix{1%sachet}. Fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir through the @water{300%ml} for the sauce and @chicken stock paste{15%g}. Bring up to the boil, then lower to a simmer. Cook, until thickened slightly, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Using a #potato masher{}, mash a third of the beans in the pan. Stir through the remaining coriander.

Add the @butter{20%g} and @honey{1%tbsp}, stir until melted and remove from the heat.

Fluff up your rice with a #fork{} and share between your serving bowls.

Spoon your frejolada over the top.

Drizzle over the @soured cream{75%g} and finish with the pickled onion and remaining coriander.

Enjoy!